
The Addis Ababa Regional Water and Sewerage Authority announced that the shortage of potable water in the capital city of Ethiopia will be solved in the last quarter of this year. Currently, the authority supplies only 60 percent of the city's potable water demand. Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, on June 12, 1997, picked the ground for Mamloo reservoir dam near Tehran, a project designed to alleviate the water shortage problem in the capital. Philippine Interior and Local Government Secretary Robert Barbers, on November 15, 1997, called on all local officials to immediately implement contingency measures to cushion the effects of El Nino, specially the shortage of water. Chinese scientists are searching for ways to alleviate China's water shortage problems through new technologies. Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye has urged residents in capital Dar es Salaam to use water sparingly as another water shortage is imminent. Water shortage in the Pakistani capital of Islamabad is expected to deteriorate as water reservoir can meet demand of the consumers just for 12 days. Addressing a one-day seminar on environment and water resources here, in December 1999, Fadi Qmeir, director-general of the Ministry of Electricity and Water Resources, attributed much of the shortage to wasted water from leaky pipes in the network. More than 170,000 children under one year of age die every year because of the shortage of potable water in Afghanistan, according to a press report reaching here, in March 2000.

